Introduction:

In the sport of Cross Country distance running, scoring has traditionally been done through a rank-sum scoring system. This system just sums up the first 5 place finishers for each team, giving a final rank for each team. While this system is quite simple and intuitive, causing it to be widely popular among runners, it does pose issues as it can lead to situations that violate the independence of irrelevant alternatives assumptions. This means that a teams performances are not independent of one another, and the presence or disappearance of a team can lead to different results. For example, in a three team meet, team one may initially win the entire thing. However, if one removes team three, team two may end up beating team one. This is an example of a violation of the IIA, and is why in these simulations we explore different scoring systems in order to see which one has the least violations of the IIA.

We have to shoutout Quang, as his simulations on the climbing and the exploration of that scoring systems was what even prompted us to explore cross country scoring. He also gave a us a couple links that were very helpful in our simulations.

Links: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0165489614000249 https://qntkhvn.netlify.app/posts/2021-07-31-climbing-p1-sim

Methods

Initially, we set up a way to simulate places and scoring of a cross country meet using a uniform distribution for places, for a specified number of teams and runners for each team. This allowed us to then code different scoring functions, like the rank sum scoring and rank product scoring functions to explore different methods of scoring a cross country meet. Rank Sum scoring, like discussed earlier simply adds the top 5 scores of each runner for a team. Rank product scoring, on the other hand, multiplies the top 5 places for each team to determine the score. This places heavy emphasis on having a runner place in the top 5/10 as it will drastically reduce the team score in comparison to rank sum scoring. We also included a drop team function, which would drop a specified team, and re-place the entire meet removing the runners from the team that was dropped. All of this allowed us to explore possible violations of the IIA as each team was dropped in a theoretical simulation. For our specific simulation, we decided to simulate the NCAA XC nationals meet, as it is the most important race of the cross country season. This meet has 31 teams, each with 7 runners each. We then utilized the different scoring functions, and dropped each of the 31 teams to see the number of IIA violations for each scoring system. We were able to use another function called count_violations, which would count the number of IIA violations that occurred in each of the 31 drops. Using this function, we were able to compare the different scoring systems to each other, and see which scoring systems had more occurrences of violations in comparison to each other.

Results

First we looked at the distributions of first-place runners across the top-five teams, and calculated the probability of getting a top five team score given you had the overall meet winner.

Rank Sum

Here we use a rank sum scoring system, were we chose the sum of the first 5 runners to be the score.

set.seed(69420)
nsim <- 10000
top10_all <- c()
top3_all <- c()
champ_all <- c()

first_runner_fourth <- c()
first_runner_fifth <- c()
a <-31
b<-7
nsim <-1000
teams_to_drop <- c(17,19)
num_scorers <- 5
#simulations looking at proportions of scoring needed for first, second, third etc
#also looks at how likely you are to win if have the winner of the meet
#could be improved by using empirical data, will attempt in future
for(i in 1:nsim){
  
  teams <- meet(a, b)
  teams_score <- teams
  a2<-ranksum_scoring(teams,num_scorers)
 
  for(i in 1:length(teams_score)){
    teams_score[[i]][length(teams_score[[i]])+1] <- a2[i]
  }
  
  teams_score <- teams_score[order(sapply(teams_score,"[[",b+1))]
  first_runner_champ <- append(first_runner_champ,teams_score[[1]][1])
  first_runner_second <- append(first_runner_second,teams_score[[2]][1])
  first_runner_third <- append(first_runner_third,teams_score[[3]][1])
  first_runner_fourth <- append(first_runner_fourth,teams_score[[4]][1])
  first_runner_fifth <- append(first_runner_fifth,teams_score[[5]][1])
  
  
  scores <- sort(a2)
  n <- scores[1:10]
  top3 <- scores[1:3]
  second <- scores[2]
  third <- scores[3]
  champ_score <- scores[1]
  champ_team <- teams_score[[1]]
  
  tenth <- scores[10]
  
  top10_all <- append(top10_all, n)
  top3_all <- append(top3_all, top3)
  champ_all <- append(champ_all, champ_score)
  second_all <- append(second_all, second)
  third_all <- append(third_all, third)
  tenth_all <- append(tenth_all,tenth)
}

#Here we utilize the count_violations function in order to determine the number of IIA violations present for Rank-Sum and Rank-Product scoring systems

set.seed(69420)
nsims <- 1000
rs_violations <- 0
rp_violations <- 0
for (i in 1:nsims){
  rs_violations <- rs_violations + count_violations(31, 7, 5, FUN = ranksum_scoring)
  rp_violations <- rp_violations + count_violations(31, 7, 5, FUN = rankproduct_scoring)
}
rs_violations
## [1] 22781
#Rank Sum IIA violations 
rp_violations
## [1] 30979
#Rank Product IIA violations

These results are quite interesting, as rank product scoring only has 22 teams out of 31000 that dont change when dropping teams. Rank sum does a lot better with the number of IIA violations, although these are still quite high at 22 thousand team changes.

Conclusions

Overall, we found that the rank-sum scoring system had a lot less IIA violations in comparison to the rank product system. We kind of figured this to be the case, as rank product is highly dependent on low placing individuals for team scoring, but to see it to the extent shown by the simulation was very surprising. As there were 31000 possible team changes(1000 simulations, 31 teams for each simulation), 30978 violations indicates that rank-product viciously violates the IIA. Rank sum is by far the better scoring system of the two, with only 22000 violations in comparison. While this is still quite a lot, there are a lot of advantages given by the scoring system in its simplicity and intuitiveness. In addition, we found that while having the individual meet winner for rank sum scoring did mean that the team had a 40% chance of being top 5 in the team scores, this figure was doubled to over 80% in the rank product scoring system. This is relevant because, in the eyes of many, an ideal cross country scoring system would place greater emphasis on the depth of the team runners. In other words, the overwhelming influence a low place finisher has in the rank product scoring system. Future simulations on different scoring systems would need to show a vast decrease in IIA violations in order to overcome both the simplicity of the rank sum scoring system and the historical precedent it has on cross country scoring.

#function for creating an XC meet with n teams of m runners with a uniform distribution
meet <- function(n, m){
  places <- rep(1:(m*n))
  teams <- list()
  for (i in 1:n){
    draw <- sample(places, m)
    draw <- sort(draw)
    teams[[i]] <- draw
    places <- places[!places %in% draw]
  }
  return (teams)
}

#function to score a meet as the sum of the ranks of b runners across a list input, teams, that contains the places of each runner
ranksum_scoring <- function(teams,b){
  scores <- c()
  for(i in 1:length(teams)){
    scores[i] <- sum(teams[[i]][1:b])
    # team[[i]][length(teams[[i]])+1] <<- scores[i] 
  }
  return(scores)
}

#function to score a meet as the product of the ranks of b runners across a list input, teams, that contains the places of each runner
rankproduct_scoring <- function(teams, b){
  scores <- rep(1, length(teams))
  for(i in 1:length(teams)){
    for (j in 1:b){
      scores[i] <- scores[i] * teams[[i]][j]
    }
  }
  return(scores)
}

#function to remove a team from a meet and then re-do the places of the runners
drop_1 <- function(teams,remove){
  teams2 <- teams
  teams_drop <- sort(unlist(teams[remove]),decreasing=TRUE)
  # print(teams_drop)
  v<- c(rep(0,length(teams[[1]])))
  v2 <- c(rep(0,length(teams[[1]])))
  for(j in 1:length(teams)){
    if((teams[j] %in% teams[remove])==FALSE){
      for(k in 1:length(teams[[j]])){
        v <- as.integer(teams_drop[k]<unlist(teams[[j]]))
        v2 <- v+v2
      }
      
      teams2[[j]] <- (teams[[j]] - v2)
      # print(j)
      # print(length(teams[[j]]))
      v2 <- c(rep(0,length(teams[[j]])))
      
    }
    
  }
  return(teams2[-remove])
}

#function that calls drop_1 in oder to remove multiple teams
drop_multiple <- function(team,mult){
  team4 <- team
  
  for(i in 1:length(mult)){
    # print(mult)
    team4 <- drop_1(team4,mult[i])
    mult <- mult-1
    # print(mult)
    
  }
  
  return(team4)
}

#Function that takes n # of teams of m runners and n_scorers scoring runners, and a scoring method, and removes every team one-by-one and counts how many times the Independence of Irrelevant Alternatives principle is violated
count_violations <- function(n, m, n_scorers, FUN = ranksum_scoring){
  teams <- meet(n, m)
  
  scores_i <- FUN(teams, n_scorers)
  team_initials <- paste("Team", c(1:n))
  scores2 <- cbind(team_initials, scores_i)
  scores2 <- scores2[order(scores2[, 2], decreasing = FALSE), ]
  
  #looping through each team being dropped, counting if IIA was violated
  n_iia_violations <- 0
  for (i in 1:n) {
    #inplace removal
    inplace <- cbind(team_initials[-i], scores_i[-i])
    inplace <- rbind(inplace, c(team_initials[i], "NA"))
    inplace <-  inplace[order(inplace[, 2], decreasing = FALSE), ]
    #dropping team
    teams2 <- drop_multiple(teams, i)
    #removing team name from label
    team_initials2 <- team_initials[-i]
    #rescoring meet aftter dropping team
    scores_i2 <- FUN(teams2, n_scorers)
    #mapping scores to teams
    scores3 <- cbind(team_initials2, scores_i2)
    #sorting by scores
    scores3 <-  scores3[order(scores3[, 2], decreasing = FALSE), ]
    #adding original team as NA
    scores3 <- rbind(scores3, c(team_initials[i], "NA"))
    #comparing inplace switch to dropping, re-placing, and rescoring, and adding it to IIA violation count
    n_iia_violations <-
      n_iia_violations + (sum(!(scores3[, 1] == inplace[, 1])) > 0)
  }
  return (n_iia_violations)
}
